	painsBodyHtml={`<p>Behind every statistic is a real caregiver — maybe you. The alarm that goes off in the middle of the night. The phone call from the doctor you take alone in the parking lot. The slow grief of watching someone you love change, mourning them before they're even gone. The friends who stopped calling because you can never get away. The version of yourself you can barely remember.</p><p>None of this means something is wrong with you. It means you're a human being pouring yourself out, day after day, with very little poured back in — and that's a weight no one was built to carry alone. There is a Father who sees the caregiver no one else is caring for, and He has something to say about who you are and how you'll make it through.</p>`}
	painsSources={[
		{ label: `AARP & National Alliance for Caregiving — Caregiving in the U.S. 2020`, url: `https://www.aarp.org/caregiving/research/caregiving-in-the-united-states.html` },
		{ label: `Pew Research Center — More than half of Americans in their 40s are 'sandwiched' between an aging parent and their own children`, url: `https://www.pewresearch.org/short-reads/2022/04/08/more-than-half-of-americans-in-their-40s-are-sandwiched-between-an-aging-parent-and-their-own-children/` },
		{ label: `CDC — Caregiving for Family and Friends: A Public Health Issue`, url: `https://www.cdc.gov/aging/caregiving/caregiver-brief.html` },
	]}
	aFatherHeading={`A Father for family caregivers`}
	aFatherBodyHtml={`<p>Here's what almost no one tells you in the middle of caregiving: the answer to the exhaustion isn't trying harder, sleeping less, or finally becoming the tireless caregiver you think you're supposed to be. The answer is a <strong style="color: var(--color-ink);">Father</strong> — a perfect, holy Father who carries you while you carry everyone else.</p><p>You were not made to be an endless well. You were made to be filled. And the One who made you doesn't measure your worth by how much you can give, how little you complain, or how long you can run on empty. He calls you His beloved child — not just the strong one, the dependable one, the one who holds it all together, but <em>you</em>, in the weariness and the grief and the days you have nothing left.</p><p>So before you're a daughter managing your mother's care, a husband at your wife's bedside, a parent who never clocks out — you are His. Your heavenly Father wants to be the strength underneath your strength, the one who says: I see what no one else sees, I am proud of you, and I am carrying you even now. Come to Me when you're weary, and I will give you rest.</p>`}
