	voicesCreditHtml={`Photos via <a href="https://commons.wikimedia.org/" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" style="color: var(--color-brand);" class="hover:underline">Wikimedia Commons</a> &mdash; Andrew Murray, George MacDonald, and Charles Spurgeon (all public domain).`}
	wordHeading={`His Word will not return void`}
	wordBodyHtml={`<p>You might not feel different the first time you read it. That's okay. The Father's love isn't a quick burst of energy to get you through the day — it's a foundation, and foundations get built quietly, one day at a time. Every verse you take in is your Father pouring something back into the one who keeps pouring out.</p><p class="mt-4" style="color: var(--color-ink);">"My word… will not return to me empty, but will accomplish that which I purpose." <span style="color: var(--color-muted);">— Isaiah 55:11</span></p>`}
	fatherSaysHeading={`What your Father says over you`}
	fatherSaysHtml={`<p>"I see what no one else sees. The middle-of-the-night wakings, the appointments you sit through alone, the grief you carry while you smile for everyone else, the fear of how much longer you can do this. And I want you to hear Me: you are Mine, and I love you right now — not just the strong you, the capable you, the one who never lets anything drop. You.</p><p>You don't have to hold it all together for Me. I am not waiting for you to do more; I am here to carry you. The love you pour out — every quiet, unseen act of it — I receive as if you did it for Me, and none of it is wasted. So come to Me when you're weary, and I will give you rest. I daily bear your burdens. I made you, and I will carry you, all the way through. I'm your Father, I delight in you, and I am not going anywhere."</p>`}
	prayerHeading={`A prayer for family caregivers`}
	prayerHtml={`<p>Our Father, we thank You and praise You for these caregivers — every son, daughter, husband, wife, and parent pouring themselves out for someone they love. Let them hear Your whisper above the exhaustion and the noise. Let them encounter Your love — not as one more demand, but as a Father's tenderness — and know they are Your beloved son or daughter, not just the strong one everyone leans on.</p><p>Father, You see what no one else sees. Steady them in the weariness, give them people who will care for them as they care for others, and carry them through the long nights and the slow grief of watching someone they love decline. I pray Your protection over them — from burnout and resentment, from the guilt that they are never doing enough, from isolation and the loss of themselves, from financial fear, and from the enemy who would steal their joy and their hope. Guard their bodies and their hearts.</p><p>Let them know there is no condemnation in You when they fall short, that the love they give is holy in Your sight, and that nothing — no exhaustion, no loss, no ending — can separate them from Your love. Renew their strength daily, fill them so they give from overflow and not from empty, and let them rest in You. And may they wake up every single day knowing they are loved by their heavenly Father.</p><p>In Jesus' name, amen.</p>`}
